16	3	1	1	assistant	Sure! Let's break down these rules one by one:\n\n1. **Every JSX expression must have one root element**:\n   - This means that all your JSX code should be wrapped inside a single parent element. For example:\n     ```jsx\n     function MyComponent() {\n       return (\n         <div>\n           <h1>Hello</h1>\n           <p>World</p>\n         </div>\n       );\n     }\n     ```\n   - Here, the `<div>` is the root element that wraps the `<h1>` and `<p>` tags.\n\n2. **Use `className` instead of `class`**:\n   - In HTML, you use the `class` attribute to add CSS classes to elements. But in JSX, you use `className` instead. For example:\n     ```jsx\n     <div className="my-class">Hello World</div>\n     ```\n   - This is because `class` is a reserved word in JavaScript, so React uses `className` to avoid conflicts.\n\n3. **JavaScript expressions go inside `{curly braces}`**:\n   - You can embed JavaScript expressions inside JSX by wrapping them in curly braces. For example:\n     ```jsx\n     function Greeting({ name }) {\n       return <h1>Hello, {name}!</h1>;\n     }\n     ```\n   - Here, `{name}` is a JavaScript expression that gets evaluated and inserted into the JSX.\n\n4. **Self-closing tags must end with `/>`**:\n   - Some HTML tags are self-closing, meaning they don't have a closing tag. In JSX, you must end these tags with a `/>`. For example:\n     ```jsx\n     <img src="image.jpg" alt="A nice image" />\n     ```\n   - This is different from HTML, where you might just write `<img src="image.jpg" alt="A nice image">`.\n\nThese rules help ensure that your JSX code is valid and works correctly with React.	/api/static/audio/tutor_3_1_1_25353.mp3	2026-03-07 15:42:58.43404
